racteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Mello","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Manuel, Jose, Carlos, Adelino, Ana, Joaquin, Acacio, Claudio, Cristina, Fernando, Americo, Enrique.  Portuguese Duarte, Joaquim, Armanda, Joao, Paulo, Serafim.","Italian: probably from a short form of a personal name ending with the hypocoristic suffix <i>-ello</i>, such as <i>Giacomello</i> from   Giacomo  .","Portuguese: variant of   Melo  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Giacomo","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Domenico, Gino, Salvatore.","Italian: from the personal name <i>Giacomo</i>, from Latin <i>Jacobus</i> via Late Latin <i>Jacomus</i> (see   James   and   Jacob  )."]},{"name":"Melle","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Heinz, Horst, Kurt, Otto.","Italian: habitational name from Melle in Cuneo province (Piedmont); in some cases possibly also a variant of a personal name such as   Mello   1.","Norwegian: probably a variant of   Mele  ."]},{"name":"Mellone","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Antonio, Emidio, Luigi, Pasquale.","Italian: from an augmentative of   Mello  ."]}]},{"name":"Dreux","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Channel Islands:  See  Druce  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Druce","meanings":["Transferred use of the Scottish surname, now used as a given name throughout the English-speaking world. In the 20th century it was particularly popular in Australia. The surname was originally a Norman baronial name, but a precise identification of the place from which it was derived has not been made (there are a large number of possible candidates). The Bruces were an influential Norman family in Scottish affairs in the early Middle Ages; its most famous member was  Robert  ‘the Bruce’ (  1274–1329 ), who is said to have drawn inspiration after his defeat at Methven from the perseverance of a spider in repeatedly climbing up again after being knocked down. He ruled Scotland as  King Robert I  from  1306 to 1329 ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Dreux de Mello I was born about 1134, in Mello, Oise, Hauts-de-France, France, his father, Dreux de Mello, was 36 and his mother, Agnès Nanteuil, was 30. He had at least 1 son and 3 daughters with Ermengarde de Toucy. He died on 3 March 1218, in his hometown, at the age of 85."},"et":{"environ 1134–3 mars 1218":"umbes 1134–3. märts 1218","1134–1218":"1134–1218","1125–1190":"1125–1190","1170–1215":"1170–1215","1172–1248":"1172–1248","1173–Female":"1173–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1100–Male":"1100–Surnud","1105–1180":"1105–1180","1190":"1190","environ 1134":"umbes 1134","before 1134":"enne 1134","1173":"1173","1172":"1172","environ 1180":"umbes 1180","1170":"1170","1180":"1180","Abt 1173":"umbes 1173","1215":"1215","1105":"1105","1248":"1248","1125":"1125","3 mars 1218":"3. märts 1218","1134":"1134","1100":"1100","1218":"1218","Mello, Oise, Hauts-de-France, France":"Mello, Oise, Hauts-de-France, Prantsusmaa","Champagne, France":"Champagne, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"environ 1134–3 mars 1218":"noin 1134–3. maaliskuuta 1218","1134–1218":"1134–1218","1125–1190":"1125–1190","1170–1215":"1170–1215","1172–1248":"1172–1248","1173–Female":"1173–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1100–Male":"1100–Kuollut","1105–1180":"1105–1180","1190":"1190","environ 1134":"noin 1134","before 1134":"ennen vuotta 1134","1173":"1173","1172":"1172","environ 1180":"noin 1180","1170":"1170","1180":"1180","Abt 1173":"noin 1173","1215":"1215","1105":"1105","1248":"1248","1125